{
  "doc_id": "10741",
  "text": "In addition to assessment of the sensitivity of the baroreflex, the number of baroreflex sequences that occur provides information concerning overall activity of this reflex [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . To find an absolute value, the occurrence number can be normalized by time [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] , by mean HR [CITATION_9] , by the number of validated sequences [CITATION_10] , or by the number of heartbeats [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] . The number of baroreflex sequences depends on the number of analyzed heartbeats, and the number of heartbeats varies among subjects and within a subject according to activity. In addition, each baroreflex sequence can have various numbers of involved heartbeats, usually ranging from three to six. Therefore, normalization of the heartbeats involved in baroreflex sequences by the total number of heartbeats in a data segment yields more realistic information on the occurrence of baroreflex sequences.",
